President Donald J. Trump will be traveling to Japan, the Republic of Korea, China, Vietnam, the Philippines, and Hawaii from November 3-14, 2017. The purpose of his trip is to emphasize the United States' commitment to alliances and partnerships in the Indo-Pacific region. In Hawaii, he will receive a briefing from the U.S. Pacific Command and visit Pearl Harbor and the USS ARIZONA Memorial. In Japan, he will meet with American and Japanese service members, hold bilateral meetings with Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, and meet with families of Japanese citizens abducted by North Korea. In the Republic of Korea, he will meet with President Moon Jae-in, visit American and South Korean service members, and speak at the National Assembly. In China, he will have meetings with President Xi Jinping. In Vietnam, he will participate in the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) Economic Leaders' Meeting and deliver a speech at the APEC CEO Summit. In the Philippines, he will attend the Special Gala Celebration Dinner for the 50th Anniversary of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and participate in the U.S.-ASEAN Summit and bilateral meetings with President Rodrigo Duterte and other leaders.